			<title>Why i use some "outdated" CSS methods?</title>
			<description>The reason I use these methods is the ease and control I have over the elements.</description>
			<author>oldpcdev</author>
			<link>https://oldpcdev.github.io/nicecss/articles/2023/02/outdated-methods.html</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 25 Feb 2023 11:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
			<content>
				<h1>Why i use some “outdated” methods?</h1>
							
				<p>I know the base of the site looks like sites from 10-15 years ago, and that's <em>on purpose</em>.</p>

				<p>The reason I use these methods is the ease and control I have over the elements.</p>
				
				<p>The secret is that when you design in a professional image editor (GIMP, Photoshop, etc...) you can increase the detail capacity of your website to make it unique.</p>
				
				<p>These details can be applied using images; Backgrounds, borders, icons and gradients.</p>
				
				<p><em>Yes</em>. I know some of these details can be added via pure CSS, but pure CSS has no soul as it's all generated by just a few lines of code. The method of images, however, does not, because it is composed of several pixels and different colors.</p>
				
				<p>Of course I use some CSS3, like @font-face and box-sizing. The fonts are not that important but the box-sizing is crucial for the structure of the elements.</p>
			</content>
